# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: certificate-pinning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In cryptography, a **certificate authority** or **certification authority** (**CA**) is an entity that stores, signs, and issues digital certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made about the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A CA acts as a trusted third party—trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The format of these certificates is specified by the X.509 or EMV standard.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] One particularly common use for certificate authorities is to sign certificates used in HTTPS, the secure browsing protocol for the World Wide Web.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Another common use is in issuing identity cards by national governments for use in electronically signing documents.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Trusted certificates can be used to create secure connections to a server via the Internet.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A certificate is essential in order to circumvent a malicious party which happens to be on the route to a target server which acts as if it were the target.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Such a scenario is commonly referred to as a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The client uses the CA certificate to authenticate the CA signature on the server certificate, as part of the authorizations before launching a secure connection.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Usually, client software—for example, browsers—include a set of trusted CA certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This makes sense, as many users need to trust their client software.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A malicious or compromised client can skip any security check and still fool its users into believing otherwise.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The clients of a CA are server supervisors who call for a certificate that their servers will bestow to users.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Commercial CAs charge money to issue certificates, and their customers anticipate the CA's certificate to be contained within the majority of web browsers, so that safe connections to the certified servers work efficiently out-of-the-box.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The quantity of web browsers, other devices, and applications which trust a particular certificate authority is referred to as ubiquity.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Mozilla, which is a non-profit business, issues several commercial CA certificates with its products.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] While Mozilla developed their own policy, the CA/Browser Forum developed similar guidelines for CA trust.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A single CA certificate may be shared among multiple CAs or their resellers.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A *root* CA certificate may be the base to issue multiple *intermediate* CA certificates with varying validation requirements.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In addition to commercial CAs, some non-profits issue publicly-trusted digital certificates without charge, for example Let's Encrypt.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Some large cloud computing and web hosting companies are also publicly-trusted CAs and issue certificates to services hosted on their infrastructure, for example IBM Cloud, Amazon Web Services, Cloudflare, and Google Cloud Platform.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Large organizations or government bodies may have their own PKIs (public key infrastructure), each containing their own CAs.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Any site using self-signed certificates acts as its own CA.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Each payment card presents along with its card data also the Card Issuer Certificate to the POS.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The Issuer Certificate is signed by EMV CA Certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The POS retrieves the public key of EMV CA from its storage, validates the Issuer Certificate and authenticity of the payment card before sending the payment request to the payment scheme.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Browsers and other clients of sorts characteristically allow users to add or do away with CA certificates at will.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] While server certificates regularly last for a relatively short period, CA certificates are further extended, so, for repeatedly visited servers, it is less error-prone importing and trusting the CA issued, rather than confirm a security exemption each time the server's certificate is renewed.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Less often, trustworthy certificates are used for encrypting or signing messages.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] CAs dispense end-user certificates too, which can be used with S/MIME.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] However, encryption entails the receiver's public key and, since authors and receivers of encrypted messages, apparently, know one another, the usefulness of a trusted third party remains confined to the signature verification of messages sent to public mailing lists.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Worldwide, the certificate authority business is fragmented, with national or regional providers dominating their home market.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This is because many uses of digital certificates, such as for legally binding digital signatures, are linked to local law, regulations, and accreditation schemes for certificate authorities.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] However, the market for globally trusted TLS/SSL server certificates is largely held by a small number of multinational companies.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This market has significant barriers to entry due to the technical requirements.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] While not legally required, new providers may choose to undergo annual security audits (such as WebTrust for certificate authorities in North America and ETSI in Europe) to be included as a trusted root by a web browser or operating system.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] As of 24 August 2020, 147 root certificates, representing 52 organizations, are trusted in the Mozilla Firefox web browser, 168 root certificates, representing 60 organizations, are trusted by macOS, and 255 root certificates, representing 101 organizations, are trusted by Microsoft Windows.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] As of Android 4.2 (Jelly Bean), Android currently contains over 100 CAs that are updated with each release.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Let's Encrypt is operated by the newly formed Internet Security Research Group, a California nonprofit recognized as federally tax-exempt.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The top spot has been held by Symantec (or VeriSign before it was purchased by Symantec) ever since [our] survey began, with it currently accounting for just under a third of all certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] As of July 2024 the survey company W3Techs, which collects statistics on certificate authority usage among the Alexa top 10 million and the Tranco top 1 million websites, lists the five largest authorities by absolute usage share as below.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The commercial CAs that issue the bulk of certificates for HTTPS servers typically use a technique called "domain validation" to authenticate the recipient of the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The techniques used for domain validation vary between CAs, but in general domain validation techniques are meant to prove that the certificate applicant controls a given domain name, not any information about the applicant's identity.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Many Certificate Authorities also offer Extended Validation (EV) certificates as a more rigorous alternative to domain validated certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Extended validation is intended to verify not only control of a domain name, but additional identity information to be included in the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Some browsers display this additional identity information in a green box in the URL bar.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Domain validation suffers from certain structural security limitations.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In particular, it is always vulnerable to attacks that allow an adversary to observe the domain validation probes that CAs send.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] These can include attacks against the DNS, TCP, or BGP protocols (which lack the cryptographic protections of TLS/SSL), or the compromise of routers.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Such attacks are possible either on the network near a CA, or near the victim domain itself.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] One of the most common domain validation techniques involves sending an email containing an authentication token or link to an email address that is likely to be administratively responsible for the domain.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This could be the technical contact email address listed in the domain's WHOIS entry, or an administrative email like admin@, administrator@, webmaster@, hostmaster@ or postmaster@ the domain.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Some Certificate Authorities may accept confirmation using root@, info@, or support@ in the domain.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The theory behind domain validation is that only the legitimate owner of a domain would be able to read emails sent to these administrative addresses.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Domain validation implementations have sometimes been a source of security vulnerabilities.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In one instance, security researchers showed that attackers could obtain certificates for webmail sites because a CA was willing to use an email address like ssladmin@domain.com for domain.com, but not all webmail systems had reserved the "ssladmin" username to prevent attackers from registering it.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Prior to 2011, there was no standard list of email addresses that could be used for domain validation, so it was not clear to email administrators which addresses needed to be reserved.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The first version of the CA/Browser Forum Baseline Requirements, adopted November 2011, specified a list of such addresses.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This allowed mail hosts to reserve those addresses for administrative use, though such precautions are still not universal.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In January 2015, a Finnish man registered the username "hostmaster" at the Finnish version of Microsoft Live and was able to obtain a domain-validated certificate for live.fi, despite not being the owner of the domain name.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A CA issues digital certificates that contain a public key and the identity of the owner.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The matching private key is not made available publicly, but kept secret by the end user who generated the key pair.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The certificate is also a confirmation or validation by the CA that the public key contained in the certificate belongs to the person, organization, server or other entity noted in the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A CA's obligation in such schemes is to verify an applicant's credentials, so that users and relying parties can trust the information in the issued certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] CAs use a variety of standards and tests to do so.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In essence, the certificate authority is responsible for saying "yes, this person is who they say they are, and we, the CA, certify that".
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] If the user trusts the CA and can verify the CA's signature, then they can also assume that a certain public key does indeed belong to whoever is identified in the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Public-key cryptography can be used to encrypt data communicated between two parties.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This can typically happen when a user logs on to any site that implements the HTTP Secure protocol.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In this example let us suppose that the user logs on to their bank's homepage www.bank.example to do online banking.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] When the user opens www.bank.example homepage, they receive a public key along with all the data that their web-browser displays.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The rest of the communication then proceeds using the new (disposable) symmetric key, so when the user enters some information to the bank's page and submits the page (sends the information back to the bank) then the data the user has entered to the page will be encrypted by their web browser.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Therefore, even if someone can access the (encrypted) data that was communicated from the user to www.bank.example, such eavesdropper cannot read or decipher it.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This mechanism is only safe if the user can be sure that it is the bank that they see in their web browser.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] If the user types in www.bank.example, but their communication is hijacked and a fake website (that pretends to be the bank website) sends the page information back to the user's browser, the fake web-page can send a fake public key to the user (for which the fake site owns a matching private key).
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The user will fill the form with their personal data and will submit the page.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The fake web-page will then get access to the user's data.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This is what the certificate authority mechanism is intended to prevent.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A certificate authority (CA) is an organization that stores public keys and their owners, and every party in a communication trusts this organization (and knows its public key).
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] When the user's web browser receives the public key from www.bank.example it also receives a digital signature of the key (with some more information, in a so-called X.509 certificate).
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The browser already possesses the public key of the CA and consequently can verify the signature, trust the certificate and the public key in it: since www.bank.example uses a public key that the certification authority certifies, a fake www.bank.example can only use the same public key.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Since the fake www.bank.example does not know the corresponding private key, it cannot create the signature needed to verify its authenticity.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] It is difficult to assure correctness of match between data and entity when the data are presented to the CA (perhaps over an electronic network), and when the credentials of the person/company/program asking for a certificate are likewise presented.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This is why commercial CAs often use a combination of authentication techniques including leveraging government bureaus, the payment infrastructure, third parties' databases and services, and custom heuristics.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In some enterprise systems, local forms of authentication such as Kerberos can be used to obtain a certificate which can in turn be used by external relying parties.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Notaries are required in some cases to personally know the party whose signature is being notarized; this is a higher standard than is reached by many CAs.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] 2. a contract relating to such transaction may not be denied legal effect, validity or enforceability solely because an electronic signature or electronic record was used in its formation.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Despite the security measures undertaken to correctly verify the identities of people and companies, there is a risk of a single CA issuing a bogus certificate to an imposter.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] It is also possible to register individuals and companies with the same or very similar names, which may lead to confusion.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] To minimize this hazard, the *certificate transparency* initiative proposes auditing all certificates in a public unforgeable log, which could help in the prevention of phishing.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In large-scale deployments, Alice may not be familiar with Bob's certificate authority (perhaps they each have a different CA server), so Bob's certificate may also include his CA's public key signed by a different CA2, which is presumably recognizable by Alice.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This process typically leads to a hierarchy or mesh of CAs and CA certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Revocation is performed by the issuing CA, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The CA/Browser Forum publishes the Baseline Requirements, a list of policies and technical requirements for CAs to follow.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] These are a requirement for inclusion in the certificate stores of Firefox and Safari.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] On April 14, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum passed a ballot to reduce SSL/TLS certificates to 47 day maximum term by March 15, 2029.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] If the CA can be subverted, then the security of the entire system is lost, potentially subverting all the entities that trust the compromised CA.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] For example, suppose an attacker, Eve, manages to get a CA to issue to her a certificate that claims to represent Alice.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] That is, the certificate would publicly state that it represents Alice, and might include other information about Alice.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Some of the information about Alice, such as her employer name, might be true, increasing the certificate's credibility.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Eve, however, would have the all-important private key associated with the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Eve could then use the certificate to send a digitally signed email to Bob, tricking Bob into believing that the email was from Alice.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Bob might even respond with encrypted email, believing that it could only be read by Alice, when Eve is actually able to decrypt it using the private key.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] A notable case of CA subversion like this occurred in 2001, when the certificate authority VeriSign issued two certificates to a person claiming to represent Microsoft.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The certificates have the name "Microsoft Corporation", so they could be used to spoof someone into believing that updates to Microsoft software came from Microsoft when they actually did not.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Microsoft and VeriSign took steps to limit the impact of the problem.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In 2008, Comodo reseller Certstar sold a certificate for mozilla.com to Eddy Nigg, who had no authority to represent Mozilla.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In 2011 fraudulent certificates were obtained from Comodo and DigiNotar, allegedly by Iranian hackers.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] There is evidence that the fraudulent DigiNotar certificates were used in a man-in-the-middle attack in Iran.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In 2012, it became known that Trustwave issued a subordinate root certificate that was used for transparent traffic management (man-in-the-middle) which effectively permitted an enterprise to sniff SSL internal network traffic using the subordinate certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In 2012, the Flame malware (also known as SkyWiper) contained modules that had an MD5 collision with a valid certificate issued by a Microsoft Terminal Server licensing certificate that used the broken MD5 hash algorithm.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The authors thus was able to conduct a collision attack with the hash listed in the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] In 2015, a Chinese certificate authority named MCS Holdings and affiliated with China's central domain registry issued unauthorized certificates for Google domains.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Google thus removed both MCS and the root certificate authority from Chrome and have revoked the certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] An attacker who steals a certificate authority's private keys is able to forge certificates as if they were CA, without needed ongoing access to the CA's systems.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Key theft is therefore one of the main risks certificate authorities defend against.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Publicly trusted CAs almost always store their keys on a hardware security module (HSM), which allows them to sign certificates with a key, but generally prevent extraction of that key with both physical and software controls.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] CAs typically take the further precaution of keeping the key for their long-term root certificates in an HSM that is kept offline, except when it is needed to sign shorter-lived intermediate certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The intermediate certificates, stored in an online HSM, can do the day-to-day work of signing end-entity certificates and keeping revocation information up to date.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] CAs sometimes use a key ceremony when generating signing keys, in order to ensure that the keys are not tampered with or copied.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The critical weakness in the way that the current X.509 scheme is implemented is that any CA trusted by a particular party can then issue certificates for any domain they choose.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Such certificates will be accepted as valid by the trusting party whether they are legitimate and authorized or not.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This is a serious shortcoming given that the most commonly encountered technology employing X.509 and trusted third parties is the HTTPS protocol.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] As all major web browsers are distributed to their end-users pre-configured with a list of trusted CAs that numbers in the dozens this means that any one of these pre-approved trusted CAs can issue a valid certificate for any domain whatsoever.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] The industry response to this has been muted.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] Given that the contents of a browser's pre-configured trusted CA list is determined independently by the party that is distributing or causing to be installed the browser application there is really nothing that the CAs themselves can do.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] This issue is the driving impetus behind the development of the DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) protocol.
[src:certificate-pinning/certificate-authority] If adopted in conjunction with Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) DANE will greatly reduce if not eliminate the role of trusted third parties in a domain's PKI.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] For example, attackers might compromise a certificate authority, and then mis-issue certificates for a web origin.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] To combat this risk, the HTTPS web server serves a list of “pinned” public key hashes valid for a given time; on subsequent connections, during that validity time, clients expect the server to use one or more of those public keys in its certificate chain.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] If it does not, an error message is shown, which cannot be (easily) bypassed by the user.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] The technique does not pin certificates, but public key hashes.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] This means that one can use the key pair to get a certificate from any certificate authority, when one has access to the private key.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] Also the user can pin public keys of root or intermediate certificates (created by certificate authorities), restricting site to certificates issued by the said certificate authority.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] Due to HPKP mechanism complexity and possibility of accidental misuse (potentially causing a lockout condition by system administrators), in 2017 browsers deprecated HPKP and in 2018 removed its support in favor of Certificate Transparency.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] The server communicates the HPKP policy to the user agent via an HTTP response header field named `Public-Key-Pins` (or `Public-Key-Pins-Report-Only` for reporting-only purposes).
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] At least one of the public keys of the certificates in the certificate chain needs to match a pinned public key in order for the chain to be considered valid by the user agent.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] At the time of publishing, RFC 7469 only allowed the SHA-256 hash algorithm.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] At least one backup key must be pinned, in case the current pinned key needs to be replaced.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] The HPKP is not valid without this backup key (a backup key is defined as a public key not present in the current certificate chain).
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] It expands on static certificate pinning, which hardcodes public key hashes of well-known websites or services within web browsers and applications.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] Most browsers disable pinning for certificate chains with private root certificates to enable various corporate content inspection scanners and web debugging tools (such as mitmproxy or Fiddler).
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] The RFC 7469 standard recommends disabling pinning violation reports for "user-defined" root certificates, where it is "acceptable" for the browser to disable pin validation.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] If the user agent performs pin validation and fails to find a valid SPKI fingerprint in the served certificate chain, it will POST a JSON formatted violation report to the host specified in the report-uri directive containing details of the violation.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] This URI may be served via HTTP or HTTPS; however, the user agent cannot send HPKP violation reports to an HTTPS URI in the same domain as the domain for which it is reporting the violation.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] Hosts may either use HTTP for the `report-uri`, use an alternative domain, or use a reporting service.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] Some browsers also support the `Public-Key-Pins-Report-Only`, which only triggers this reporting while not showing an error to the user.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] During its peak adoption, HPKP was reported to be used by 3,500 of top 1 million internet sites, a figure that declined to 650 around the end of 2019.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] Criticism and concern revolved around malicious or human error scenarios known as HPKP Suicide and RansomPKP.
[src:certificate-pinning/http-public-key-pinning] In such scenarios, a website owner would have their ability to publish new contents to their domain severely hampered by either losing access to their own keys or having new keys announced by a malicious attacker.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] In this scenario, the attacker must be able to intercept all relevant messages passing between the two victims and inject new ones.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] This is straightforward in many circumstances; for example, an attacker within range of a Wi-Fi access point hosting a network without encryption could insert themselves as a man in the middle.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] As it aims to circumvent mutual authentication, a MITM attack can succeed only when the attacker impersonates each endpoint sufficiently well to satisfy their expectations.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Most cryptographic protocols include some form of endpoint authentication specifically to prevent MITM attacks.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] For example, TLS can authenticate one or both parties using a mutually trusted certificate authority.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Suppose Alice wishes to communicate with Bob.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Meanwhile, Mallory wishes to intercept the conversation to eavesdrop (breaking confidentiality) with the option to deliver a false message to Bob under the guise of Alice (breaking non-repudiation).
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Mallory would perform a man-in-the-middle attack as described in the following sequence of events.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Mallory relays this message to Bob; Bob cannot tell it is not really from Alice: Alice Mallory *"Hi Bob, it's Alice.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Bob thinks that this message is a secure communication from Alice.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] This example shows the need for Alice and Bob to have a means to ensure that they are truly each using each other's public keys, and not the public key of an attacker.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Otherwise, such attacks are generally possible, in principle, against any message sent using public-key technology.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] There are several attack types that can fall into the category of MITM.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] SSL/TLS stripping: Downgrades HTTPS traffic to HTTP, intercepting and reading unencrypted data.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] ARP spoofing: Sends fake ARP messages to associate the attacker’s MAC address with a target IP, intercepting local network traffic.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] DNS spoofing or poisoning: Redirects DNS queries to malicious servers, leading victims to fake websites.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Session hijacking: Steals session cookies or tokens to impersonate a legitimate user in an active session.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Man-in-the-browser (MITB): Malware alters browser activity, intercepting or manipulating transactions in real-time.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Wi-Fi MITM (evil twin attack): Creates a fake Wi-Fi hotspot to intercept communications from connected devices.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Email hijacking: Intercepts email exchanges to manipulate or steal sensitive information.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Replay attacks: Captures and retransmits valid data to repeat actions or disrupt communication.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Fake certificate authority (CA): Uses a fraudulent CA to sign fake certificates, tricking victims into trusting malicious connections.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] MITM attacks can be prevented or detected by two means: authentication and tamper detection.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Authentication provides some degree of certainty that a given message has come from a legitimate source.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Tamper detection merely shows evidence that a message may have been altered and has broken integrity.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] All cryptographic systems that are secure against MITM attacks provide some method of authentication for messages.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Most require an exchange of information (such as public keys) in addition to the message over a secure channel.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Such protocols, often using key-agreement protocols, have been developed with different security requirements for the secure channel, though some have attempted to remove the requirement for any secure channel at all.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] A public key infrastructure, such as Transport Layer Security, may harden Transmission Control Protocol against MITM attacks.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] In such structures, clients and servers exchange certificates which are issued and verified by a trusted third party called a certificate authority (CA).
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] If the original key to authenticate this CA has not been itself the subject of a MITM attack, then the certificates issued by the CA may be used to authenticate the messages sent by the owner of that certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Use of mutual authentication, in which both the server and the client validate the other's communication, covers both ends of a MITM attack.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] If the server or client's identity is not verified or deemed as invalid, the session will end.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] However, the default behavior of most connections is to only authenticate the server, which means mutual authentication is not always employed and MITM attacks can still occur.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Attestments, such as verbal communications of a shared value (as in ZRTP), or recorded attestments such as audio/visual recordings of a public key hash are used to ward off MITM attacks, as visual media is much more difficult and time-consuming to imitate than simple data packet communication.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] However, these methods require a human in the loop in order to successfully initiate the transaction.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] While HTTP Public Key Pinning (HPKP) was originally designed to prevent MITM attacks involving compromised certificate authorities, it has been deprecated by major browsers due to its high risk of accidental site bricking.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] It has been widely superseded by Certificate Transparency (CT), which mandates that all TLS certificates be logged in publicly auditable records to detect fraudulent or unauthorized certificates in real time.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] DNSSEC extends the DNS protocol to use signatures to authenticate DNS records, preventing simple MITM attacks from directing a client to a malicious IP address.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Latency examination can potentially detect the attack in certain situations, such as with long calculations that lead into tens of seconds like hash functions.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] To detect potential attacks, parties check for discrepancies in response times.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] For example: Say that two parties normally take a certain amount of time to perform a particular transaction.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] If one transaction, however, were to take an abnormal length of time to reach the other party, this could be indicative of a third party's presence interfering with the connection and inserting additional latency in the transaction.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Quantum cryptography, in theory, provides tamper-evidence for transactions through the no-cloning theorem.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Protocols based on quantum cryptography typically authenticate part or all of their classical communication with an unconditionally secure authentication scheme.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] As an example Wegman-Carter authentication.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Captured network traffic from what is suspected to be an attack can be analyzed in order to determine whether there was an attack and, if so, determine the source of the attack.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] A Stingray phone tracker is a cellular phone surveillance device that mimics a wireless carrier cell tower in order to force all nearby mobile phones and other cellular data devices to connect to it.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] The tracker relays all communications back and forth between cellular phones and cell towers.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] In 2011, a security breach of the Dutch certificate authority DigiNotar resulted in the fraudulent issuing of certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Subsequently, the fraudulent certificates were used to perform MITM attacks.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] In 2013, Nokia's Xpress Browser was revealed to be decrypting HTTPS traffic on Nokia's proxy servers, giving the company clear text access to its customers' encrypted browser traffic.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Nokia responded by saying that the content was not stored permanently, and that the company had organizational and technical measures to prevent access to private information.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] In 2017, Equifax withdrew its mobile phone apps following concern about MITM vulnerabilities.
[src:certificate-pinning/man-in-the-middle-attack] Bluetooth, a wireless communication protocol, has also been susceptible to man-in-the-middle attacks due to its wireless transmission of data.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The Pinning Cheat Sheet is a technical guide to implementing certificate and public key pinning as discussed by Jeffrey Walton at the Virginia chapter's presentation Securing Wireless Channels in the Mobile Space.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] This guide is focused on providing clear, simple, actionable guidance for securing the channel in a hostile environment where actors could be malicious and the conference of trust a liability.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Users, developers, and applications expect security on their communication channels, but some channels may not meet this expectation.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Channels built using well known protocols like SSL, and TLS can be vulnerable to Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) attacks if certificate-based trusts are misused.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The attacker is able to inject a dangerous CA into the client’s trust store.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] In the case of the latter issue, an attacker with the access to update a trust store will have the access to change the workings of the mobile application, potentially defeating pinning.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] As Certificate and Public Key Pinning makes clear, this problem is very small due to years of security advancements by the certificate authority and browser communities.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Pinning is the process of associating a host with their *expected* X509 certificate or public key.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Once a certificate or public key is known or seen for a host, the certificate or public key is associated or 'pinned' to the host.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] If more than one certificate or public key is acceptable, then the program holds a *pinset* (taken from Jon Larimer and Kenny Root Google I/O talk).
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] In this case, the advertised credential must match one of the elements in the pinset.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] A host or service's certificate or public key can be added to an application at development time, it can be added upon first encountering the certificate or public key (an approach commonly known as “Trust On First Use”, or TOFU), or it can be added and updated in real time via an unpinned channel.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The former - adding at development time - is preferred since *preloading* the certificate or public key *out-of-band* usually means the attacker cannot taint the pin.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Keep in mind that this "when" is about at what point in time you pin.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The first question should be, “Should I Pin?”.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] There is almost no situation where you should consider pinning.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The risk of outages almost always outweighs any security risks given advances in security.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] If you consider pinning, you should read Certificate and Public Key Pinning and fully understand the threat model.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] If you are working for an organization which practices "egress filtering" as part of a Data Loss Prevention (DLP) strategy, you will likely encounter *Interception Proxies*.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] We like to refer to these things as **"good" bad actors** (as opposed to **"bad" bad actors**) since both break end-to-end security and we can't tell them apart.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] In this case, **do not** offer to allow-list the interception proxy since it defeats your security goals.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Add the interception proxy's public key to your pinset after being **instructed** to do so by the folks in Risk Acceptance.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The idea is to reuse the existing protocols and infrastructure, but use them in a hardened manner.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] For reuse, a program would keep doing the things it used to do when establishing a secure connection.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] To harden the channel, the program would take advantage of the `OnConnect` callback offered by a library, framework or platform.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] In the callback, the program would verify the remote host's identity by validating its certificate or public key.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] In order to decide what should be pinned you can follow the following steps.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] For example, the application pins the remote endpoint leaf certificate but includes a backup pin for the intermediate CA.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] This increases the risk by trusting more certificate authorities but decreases the chances of bricking your app.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] If there's any issue with the leaf certificate, the app can always fall back to the intermediate CA until you release an app update.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The three choices are explained below in more detail.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] You are encouraged to pin the `subjectPublicKeyInfo` because it has the public parameters (such as `{e,n}` for an RSA public key) **and** contextual information such as an algorithm and OID.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The context will help you keep your bearings at times, and the figure to the right shows the additional information available.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] You can fetch the certificate out of band for the website, have the IT folks email your company certificate to you, use `openssl s_client` to retrieve the certificate, etc.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] At runtime, you can retrieve the website or server's certificate in a callback.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Within the callback, you compare the retrieved certificate with the certificate embedded within the program.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] If the comparison fails, then fail the method or function, log it on the client-side and alert the end user.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] If your threat model warrants pinning, understand that users will click past any warnings, so do not give the user an option to proceed and bypass the pin.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Public key pinning is more flexible but a little trickier due to the extra steps necessary to extract the public key from a certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] As with a certificate, the program checks the extracted public key with its embedded copy of the public key.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Given that most certificates today are only good for 90 days, using public key pinning can also make the timeline for updating pinsets longer, as you can pin a key where the certificate has not even been issued yet.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] While the three choices above used DER encoding, it's also acceptable to use a hash of the information.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] In fact, the original sample programs were written using digested certificates and public keys.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The samples were changed to allow a programmer to inspect the objects with tools like `dumpasn1` and other ASN.1 decoders.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] This section discusses certificate and public key pinning in Android Java, iOS, .Net, and OpenSSL.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Code has been omitted for brevity, but the key points for the platform are highlighted.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Since Android N, the preferred way for implementing pinning is by leveraging Android's Network Security Configuration feature, which lets apps customize their network security settings in a safe, declarative configuration file without modifying app code.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] To enable pinning, the `<pin-set>` configuration setting can be used.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Alternatively you can use methods such as the pinning from OkHTTP in order to set specific pins programmatically, as explained in the OWASP Mobile Security Testing Guide (MSTG) and the OKHttp documentation.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] The Android documentation provides an example of how SSL validation can be customized within the app's code (in order to implement pinning) in the Unknown CA implementation document.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] However, implementing pinning validation from scratch should be avoided, as implementation mistakes are extremely likely and usually lead to severe vulnerabilities.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Lastly, if you want to validate whether the pinning is successful, please follow instructions from the introduction into testing network communication and the Android specific network testing chapters of the OWASP Mobile Security Testing Guide (MSTG).
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Apple suggests pinning a CA public key by specifying it in `Info.plist` file under App Transport Security Settings.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] More details in the article "Identity Pinning: How to configure server certificates for your app".
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] TrustKit, an open-source SSL pinning library for iOS and macOS is available.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] It provides an easy-to-use API for implementing pinning, and has been deployed in many apps.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Otherwise, more details regarding how SSL validation can be customized on iOS (in order to implement pinning) are available in the HTTPS Server Trust Evaluation technical note.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Lastly, if you want to validate whether the pinning is successful, please follow instructions from the introduction into testing network communication and the iOS specific network testing chapters of the OWASP Mobile Security Testing Guide (MSTG).
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] .Net pinning can be achieved by using `ServicePointManager`.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] An example can be found at the OWASP MSTG.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Pinning can occur at one of two places with OpenSSL.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] First is the user supplied `verify_callback`.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Second is after the connection is established via `SSL_get_peer_certificate`.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Either method will allow you to access the peer's certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Though OpenSSL performs the X509 checks, you must fail the connection and tear down the socket on error.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] By design, a server that does not supply a certificate will result in `X509_V_OK` with a **NULL** certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] You must call `SSL_get_peer_certificate` and verify the certificate is **non-NULL**.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] electron-ssl-pinning, an open-source SSL pinning library for Electron based applications.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] It provides an easy-to-use API for implementing pinning and also provides a tool for fetching configuration based on needed hosts.
[src:certificate-pinning/pinning-cheat-sheet] Otherwise, you can validate certificates by yourself using ses.setCertificateVerifyProc(proc).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:certificate-pinning/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] In the SSH protocol, most client software (though not all) will, upon connecting to a not-yet-trusted server, display the server's public key fingerprint, and prompt the user to verify they have indeed authenticated it using an authenticated channel.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The client will then record the trust relationship into its trust database.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] New identifier will cause a blocking warning that requires manual removal of the currently stored identifier.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The XMPP client Conversations uses Blind Trust Before Verification, where all identifiers are blindly trusted until the user demonstrates will and ability to authenticate endpoints by scanning the QR-code representation of the identifier.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] After the first identifier has been scanned, the client will display a shield symbol for messages from authenticated endpoints, and red background for others.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] In Signal the endpoints initially blindly trust the identifier and display non-blocking warnings when it changes.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The identifier can be verified either by scanning a QR-code, or by exchanging the decimal representation of the identifier (called Safety Number) over an authenticated channel.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The identifier can then be marked as verified.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] This changes the nature of identifier change warnings from non-blocking to blocking.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Jami and Ricochet the identifier is the user's call-sign itself.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The ID can be exchanged over any channel, but until the identifier is verified over an authenticated channel, it is effectively blindly trusted.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The identifier change also requires an account change, thus a MITM attack for same account requires access to endpoint's private key.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] In WhatsApp the endpoint initially blindly trusts the identifier, and by default no warning is displayed when the identifier changes.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] If the user demonstrates will and ability to authenticate endpoints by accessing the key fingerprint (called Security Code), the client will prompt the user to enable non-blocking warnings when the identifier changes.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The WhatsApp client does not allow the user to mark the identifier as verified.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] In Telegram's optional secret chats the endpoints blindly trust the identifier.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Changed identifier spawns a new secret chat window instead of displaying any warning.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The identifiers can be verified by comparing the visual or hexadecimal representation of the identifier.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The Telegram client does not allow the user to mark the identifier as verified.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] In Keybase the clients can cross-sign each other's keys, which means trusting a single identifier allows verification of multiple identifiers.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Keybase acts as a trusted third party that verifies a link between a Keybase account and the account's signature chain that contains the identifier history.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The identifier used in Keybase is either the hash of the root of the user's signature chain, or the Keybase account name tied to it.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Until the user verifies the authenticity of the signature chain's root hash (or the keybase account) over an authenticated channel, the account and its associated identifiers are essentially blindly trusted, and the user is susceptible to a MITM attack.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The single largest strength of any TOFU-style model is that a human being must initially validate every interaction.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] A common application of this model is the use of ssh-rpc 'bot' users between computers, whereby public keys are distributed to a set of computers for automated access from centralized hosts.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The TOFU aspect of this application forces a sysadmin (or other trusted user) to validate the remote server's identity upon first connection.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] For end-to-end encrypted communication the TOFU model allows authenticated encryption without the complex procedure of obtaining a personal certificate which are vulnerable to CA Compromise.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Compared to Web of Trust, TOFU has less maintenance overhead.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The largest weakness of TOFU that requires manual verification is its inability to scale for large groups or computer networks.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The maintenance overhead of keeping track of identifiers for every endpoint can quickly scale beyond the capabilities of the users.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] In environments where the authenticity of the identifier cannot be verified easily enough (for example, the IT staff of workplace or educational facility might be hard to reach), the users tend to blindly trust the identifier of the opposing endpoint.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Accidentally approved identifiers of attackers may also be hard to detect if the man-in-the-middle attack persists.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] As a new endpoint always involves a new identifier, no warning about potential attack is displayed.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] This has caused misconception among users that it's safe to proceed without verifying the authenticity of the initial identifier, regardless of whether the identifier is presented to the user or not.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Warning fatigue has pushed many messaging applications to remove blocking warnings to prevent users from reverting to less secure applications that do not feature end-to-end encryption in the first place.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Out-of-sight identifier verification mechanisms reduce the likelihood that secure authentication practices are discovered and adopted by the users.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The first known formal use of the term TOFU or TUFU was by CMU researchers Dan Wendlandt, David Andersen, and Adrian Perrig in their research paper "Perspectives: Improving SSH-Style Host Authentication With Multi-Path Probing" published in 2008 at the Usenix Annual Technical Conference.
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] Moxie Marlinspike mentioned Perspectives and the term TOFU the DEF CON 18 proceedings, with reference to comments made by Dan Kaminsky, during the panel discussion "An Open Letter, A Call to Action".
[src:certificate-pinning/trust-on-first-use] The topics of trust, validation, non-repudiation are fundamental to all work in the field of cryptography and digital security.
